The paper deals with the problem of recovering a sparse weight vector from a set of noisy linear combinations, which is a common problem in signal processing and machine learning. The paper proposes a method to reduce the computational cost of the matrix completion step by ignoring the columns corresponding to zero elements in the sparse vector. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the Information Theory (cs.IT) sub-category, which deals with the study of information processing, transmission, and storage. Additionally, the paper proposes a unified four-step problem for partial matrix completion and sparse vector recovery, which involves techniques from machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and numerical analysis (cs.NA). Finally, the paper also mentions applications in massive MIMO and medical data, which suggests that it may also belong to the Signal Processing (cs.SI) sub-category.
